  "prompt": "What is the appropriate way to use Ms., Mrs., and Miss?",
  "response": "The appropriate use of Ms., Mrs., and Miss depends primarily on a woman's marital status and personal preference. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Miss:** Used for unmarried women. Traditionally used for younger, unmarried women, but is still appropriate for unmarried women of any age who prefer it.\n\n*   **Mrs.:** Used for married women.\n\n*   **Ms.:** This is a title that doesn't specify marital status. It can be used for any woman, regardless of whether she is married or not. It's often the best choice when you don't know a woman's marital status, or if she prefers not to be defined by it.\n\n**General Guidelines and Considerations:**\n\n*   **Respect Personal Preference:** The most important thing is to respect a woman's preference. If you know how she prefers to be addressed, use that title.\n*   **When in Doubt, Use Ms.:** If you are unsure of a woman's marital status or preference, \"Ms.\" is generally considered the safest and most respectful option.\n*   **Formal vs. Informal:** In very formal settings, traditional titles might still be more common (though \"Ms.\" remains a viable option). However, in most modern contexts, erring on the side of neutrality is usually preferred.\n*   **Professional Settings:** \"Ms.\" is almost always appropriate in professional settings unless you know the individual prefers otherwise.\n*   **Consistency:** Once you know a woman's preferred title, be consistent in using it.\n*   **Use with Full Name:** When using any of these titles, it's typically followed by the woman's last name (e.g., Ms. Johnson, Mrs. Smith, Miss Davis).\n\n**Example Scenarios:**\n\n*   You're writing a formal letter to a woman whose marital status you don't know: Use Ms. [Last Name].\n*   You're introducing a married woman to a group, and you know she prefers to be called Mrs.: Use Mrs. [Last Name].\n*   You're talking to a young woman who introduces herself as \"Miss [Last Name]\": Use Miss [Last Name].\n*   You're unsure of a woman's preference at a networking event: Use Ms. [Last Name] until you learn otherwise.\n\n**In summary:**\n*   Prioritize a woman's stated preference.\n*   When unsure, use \"Ms.\" This is the most versatile and often the most respectful option in modern usage.\n*   Avoid making assumptions about a woman's marital status based on her age or appearance.\n",
